<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-06-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-06-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="369" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d369">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00/15127½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-06-02">
                                    <hi rend="italic">2 June, 1915</hi>
                                </date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I like those
                            suggestions very much indeed, and hope that when the proper time comes
                            you will act on them.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>P. S. It is very interesting that Lansing should have made the same
                                suggestion about the closing words of the statement. It furnished me
                                with exactly what I was looking for.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>W. W.</signed>
                            </closer>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>